> Served with nutty brown rice and quinoa, lots of fresh lime juice and chopped
> fresh coriander, this 20-minute paneer and sweet potato curry is a great
> mid-week vegetarian recipe. Paneer is a fresh, mild and dense cheese that
> doesn't melt, so it's a great thing to pair with the bold flavours in this
> dish. It is a popular ingredient across India and much of Southern Asia, and
> provides bulk and protein to veggie curries like this one.

Heat a splash of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} over medium-high heat.

When hot, add the @sweet potato{300%g}(diced) and fry, stirring frequently
until beginning to soften, ~{5%minutes}.

Chop the @paneer{250%g} into 2cm chunks and add to the frying pan.

Trim the @courgette{1}, quarter lengthways then chop widthways into small
pieces.

Roughly chop the @coriander{1}(stalks and leaves separated) (stalks and all).

Zest and halve the @lime{1/2}.

Add the @Jalfrezi spice mix{1%tbsp}, @ground turmeric{1%tsp} and
@giner puree{1/2%tsp} to the frying pan. Stir and cook for ~{1%minute}.

Pour in the @light coconut milk{400%ml} and @vegetable stock powder{1/2%tsp},
stir and lower to a simmer.

Season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{} and simmer for ~{5%minutes}.

While the curry simmers away, have a quick tidy up.

Add the courgette and cook until soft enough to eat, another ~{5%minutes}.
Stir occasionally.

Meanwhile cook the @brown rice & quinoa{1%pack} according to the pack
instructions.

Get ready to serve.

Share the rice and quinoa between #bowls{} and sprinkle on a little lime
zest.

Add the remaining lime zest to the curry and stir in half the coriander and a
good squeeze of lime juice.

Season to taste with salt and pepper.

Spoon the curry on top of your rice, finish with a sprinkling of remaining
coriander. TUCK IN!